@1175 = ~Plate Armor~
@1176 = ~Duskwood Plate~
@1177 = ~This finely crafted suit of armor is fashioned from layered duskwood—an ancient, iron-hard timber known for its resilience and quiet grace. Though shaped in the form of full plate, its organic structure and natural resonance allow even single-class druids to don it without breaking their sacred oaths.

Woven into the wood are subtle enchantments of druidic origin. While it offers the solid defense of conventional plate, it remains lighter and more attuned to natural energy, resisting corruption and warding off unnatural decay. Those who wear it say the scent of wet leaves and moss lingers faintly within.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Fire Resistance: -10%
– Electricity Resistance: +10%
– Saving Throws vs. Death: +1

Armor Class: 3 (0 vs. slashing)
Requires:
 8 Strength

Weight: 20~
@1178 = ~Potion~
@1179 = ~Potion of Natural Attunement~
@1180 = ~This murky green potion exudes the scent of wet bark and crushed leaves. It was designed by druids who believe that all true growth comes through greater sacrifice.

Upon drinking the entire potion, the user feels a subtle shift in <PRO_HISHER> being—strength wanes, but something healing stirs. In surrendering brute force, the body opens to the quiet powers of rejuvenation—an ancient balance, restored through loss.

Such potions are rare and respected, for they teach what every tree already knows: that what is shed may nourish something greater.

STATISTICS:

Charge ability:
– Drinking the potion permanently lowers the character’s Strength by 1, but grants Cure Serious Wounds or Neutralize Poison (50% chance each) as an innate ability

Weight: 1~
@1181 = ~Wand~
@1182 = ~Wand of Goodberry~
@1183 = ~This slender wand appears to have grown rather than been carved—it is shaped from a single twisting branch, smooth to the touch and still warm with life. At either end, tiny berries have sprouted, glowing faintly with druidic magic.

Though humble in form, this wand holds the power to conjure Goodberries, just like the druidic spell. These enchanted fruits offer nourishment, restore vitality, and provide comfort in the wilds—each a small gift of peace in a world too often torn by blade and flame.

STATISTICS:

– May cast Goodberry per charge

Requires:
 9 Wisdom

Weight: 1~

@1184 = ~Face of the Forest~
@1185 = ~This mask seems to shift gently with every breath of wind. Its features resemble a serene face—neither elf nor human, but something older, wilder. By donning the mask, the wearer feels the quiet strength of the forest. In daylight, when the sun touches leaf and root, its magic quickens the blood and mends small wounds. The mask’s natural fibers harden under threat, offering both physical protection and uncanny resilience against deadly blows.

Another power, when invoked, is the way certain mammals respond to the wearer—with unexpected calm, even trust. From field mouse to forest bear, creatures of fur and fang seem to ignore the being behind the mask.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +1
– Regenerates 1 Hit Point per round while within a forest.
– Protects against critical hits

Charge abilities:
– Cast protection from animals once per day: Casting this spell causes all non-magical mammals to disregard the wearer of the mask for one turn.

Weight: 1~
@1186 = ~Chestnut Bullet +2~
@1187 = ~These magically hardened sling bullets are made from wild chestnuts—still bearing their natural spines. Originally enchanted by a halfling named Tipple Fernburrow to scare off a pack of hungry goblins, they’ve since found favor with pranksters and wanderers across the Western Heartlands. Despite their humble appearance, they strike with surprising force—and a sting you won’t soon forget.

STATISTICS:

THAC0: +2
Damage: 1d4+3 (missile), +2 piercing damage
Launcher: Sling

Weight: 0~
@1188 = ~This ancient elven armor has long since seen its prime. Once finely crafted and bearing the elegance of its people, it is now dulled, cracked, and fragile with age. Whatever enchantments or strength it once held have faded to dust, leaving only a shell unfit for battle.

STATISTICS:

Weight: 20~
@1189 = ~Jagged Script~
@1190 = ~The script is crude and jagged, yet disturbingly deliberate. It reads:

Patience, patience... centuries of it, and still the prize lies just beyond my reach. The elf’s flesh, locked tight by foolish wards. But even the strongest seal can be undone by mortal hands too curious for their own good.
Find one. Any one. Whisper promises. Let them break the seal on her tomb for me.
Then... I shall have a body again. A perfect one. A vessel worthy of my hunger.~
@1191 = ~Plaguestaff~
@1192 = ~Carved from the heartwood of a long-dead tree, this staff radiates a faint odor of decay. It is said to have been gifted by Talona herself to a mortal champion whose very touch brought weakness and fever. The Plaguestaff does not strike to kill swiftly; it spreads languor, sickness, and inevitability—until the victim's strength falters entirely.

To wield it is to channel the patient cruelty of disease, and the knowledge that all life withers in time.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Immunity to disease
– +2 bonus to Saving Throws vs. Death

Combat abilities:
– On Hit: 5% chance to inflict Withering Sickness – target must Save vs. Death or lose 1d2 Strength for 4 hours (stacking)

Charge abilities:
– Poison Strike (1/day): For the next 3 rounds, each hit poisons the target (2d6 damage per round for 3 rounds, Save vs. Death halves duration)

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d6+3 (crushing)
Speed Factor: 1
Proficiency Type: Quarterstaff
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 5 Strength

Weight: 3~
@1193 = ~Arrows of Charming~
@1194 = ~These finely crafted arrows are unlike any of mundane make. Their tips are delicately shaped into hearts of polished coral, glimmering faintly in the light. It is said they were fashioned by the sirines of the Sword Coast, not for war, but for persuasion — each arrow carrying a whisper of its maker’s beguiling song. When loosed, they seek not to harm, but to sway the will of the target, drawing them toward the archer’s cause.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– Target must save vs. Spell or be charmed for 5 rounds

THAC0: +1
Damage: 0 (missile)
Launcher: Bow

Weight: 0~
@1195 = ~Poisoned Bullets~
@1196 = ~These sling bullets are coated in a thick, foul-smelling contact poison. Upon impact, it seeps into the wound, causing a grievous affliction.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– Hit target must save vs. Death or suffer 2 points of poison damage per second for 10 seconds

THAC0: +1
Damage: 1d4+1
Damage type: Missile
Launcher: Sling

Weight: 0~
@1197 = ~Witherbranch~
@1198 = ~This cruel club appears to be nothing more than a gnarled, blackened bough, its surface split and twisted as if writhing in pain. It was cut from a tree deep within a plague-ridden grove, where Talona’s breath had stilled all life. Its thorns gleam with a dull green patina — residue from years of venomous anointing. Wielded in battle, the Witherbranch delivers not only a bruising blow, but the creeping embrace of rot.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
–  Talona's Kiss: While the wielder is poisoned, <PRO_HESHE> gains a +5 bonus to all saving throws and attack rolls until the poison subsides.  

Combat abilities:
– Hit target must save vs. Death or suffer 1 point of poison damage per second for 6 seconds in 50% of hits

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d6+3 (crushing)
Speed Factor: 1
Proficiency Type: Club
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 5 Strength

Weight: 1~
@1199 = ~Gauntlets of the Treant~
@1200 = ~These massive gauntlets are formed of bark and living root, bound with strips of ironwood. Their surface shifts slightly, as if the gauntlets still draw strength from unseen soil. Druids tell that they were crafted in reverence to the treants of the Forest of Tethir, guardians as patient as the earth itself.
When the wearer’s flesh is hardened with Barkskin, the gauntlets channel that living armor into raw strength, allowing the bearer to strike with the might of a towering oak.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– +2 Strength while Barkskin is active

Weight: 2~
@1201 = ~Amulet of Inner Stillness~
@1202 = ~This plain wooden amulet, set with a single green pearl, bears no inscription. It is said to have been blessed in the still waters of Eldath. When silence falls upon its wearer, a deep inner peace rises instead, shielding the mind from all intrusive forces. Neither confusion nor charms, domination nor stunning magic can shake the quiet center of the soul.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– While Silenced: Immunity to Suggestion, Charm, Domination, Command, Sleep, Maze, Stun, Confusion and Psionic Blast.

Weight: 1~
@1203 = ~Honeymead of Duskwood Dell~
@1204 = ~This heavy cask is filled with golden mead brewed by an Eldathyn monk in Duskwood Dell. The nectar carries the fragrance of wild blossoms and the patient work of countless bees.

The monk has entrusted you with this cask, asking that you deliver it to Samuel Thunderburp, proprietor of the Five Flagons in Athkatla. Once you have received payment, you are to return the gold to the monk so that it may serve the temples and gardens of Eldath.

Weight: 1~
@1205 = ~Cloak of Thousand Stings~
@1206 = ~This cloak of thick brown cloth is pitted and punctured with countless tiny holes, as though it had long served as the last defense against a thousand stings and arrows. Despite its battered look, the fabric hums faintly with protective power. It smells of smoke, wax, and honey.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +1 vs. missiles and piercing weapons
– Immunity to "Summon Insects" and "Insect Plague"

Weight: 3~
@1207 = ~This emerald-hued crystal rose is said to be a gift from Mythrien Sarath, the Watcher over Mythals. Each of its fragile petals glimmers with a light not of this world, as though echoing the lost wards of ancient elven cities.
When a petal is plucked, a translucent sphere surrounds the bearer, shielding <PRO_HIMHER> from spells of lesser potency. Yet the gift is fleeting—no one can know how many petals remain, and when the last one falls, the rose will crumble to dust.

STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– Pluck a Petal: Grants immunity to spells of up to 5th level for 3 rounds
– Limited number of uses (unknown to the bearer); the rose vanishes when depleted

Weight: 0~
@1208 = ~Elminster's Ecologies: Appendix IVa~
@1209 = ~Elminster's Ecologies: Appendix IVa

This time-worn tome is written by the sage Elminster, and apparently part of a much larger body of work containing detailed studies of most of the strange creatures from around Faerûn. 

The appendix seems to refer to newly-discovered variations on normal breeds of creatures. Of particular interest:

"Will-o’-the-Wisps (Common)
These pale, floating lights haunt marshes and ruins, feeding on fear. They lure travelers astray and strike with crackling bursts of lightning. Hard to harm with steel or spell, they remain among the most treacherous of minor undead."

"Will-o’Wild
A mutation born of unstable magic. Flickering in ever-changing flashes, these lights twist spells around them—wards collapse, surges erupt, enchantments go awry. They are most often found drifting in regions of wild magic."

"Will-o’Dead
Spawn of lifeless Weave. These wan globes feed not on fear but on power: They sap prepared spells and drain charges from wands and staves. They linger where magic itself has failed, in the barren zones known as dead magic."~
@1210 = ~Essence of the Will-o’Dead~
@1211 = ~A faintly glowing mote of pallid light, cold to the touch and unnervingly silent. Within it lingers the hollow hunger of dead magic, a force that drains spell and staff alike. Lore-whispers suggest that such an essence could one day serve to counter the emptiness where the Weave has failed.~
@1212 = ~Essence of the Will-o’Wild~
@1213 = ~This shimmering fragment pulses with chaotic hues, shifting from emerald to amber in an instant. It carries within it the untamed spark of wild magic, unpredictable yet potent. Some claim that such essence, properly bound, might shield its bearer from the turbulence of unstable Weave-fields.~ 
@1214 = ~Manual of Peaceful Living~
@1215 = ~Manual of Peaceful Living
This contemplative tome  offers guidance on living a life of serenity and restraint. By learning to set aside violence, the reader loses one attack per round. Yet in return, <PRO_HESHE> gains a permanent boon of calm resilience: +1 to all saving throws, and a natural grace that grants +1 to Armor Class.

As with all such rare works, the book vanishes after a single use.

STATISTICS:

Attacks per Round: Reduced by 1 (permanently)
Armor Class: Improved by 1 (permanently)
Saving Throws: +1 bonus (permanently)
Special: The book is consumed upon use
Usage: Place into quick item slot

Weight: 25~

// script strings
@2000 = ~Duskwood Dell~
@2001 = ~Eldath, goddess of peace and calm waters~
@2002 = ~A profound sense of peace washes over you in this place. You feel utterly incapable of raising a weapon here.~
@2003 = ~As you approach the gate leading to the lower levels, you feel a flicker of magic. It seems the corrupted mythal does not reach into the depths—meaning your magic should function normally in the areas below.~
@2004 = ~Upon entering the ruined elven city, you feel the shattered remnants of the mythal coil around you—its once-pure magic now twisted into a volatile blend of wild surges and dead magic.~
@2005 = ~You must place both pieces of a necklace upon the anvil to reforge them into one.~
@2006 = ~With the aid of the magical anvil, you are able to reforge the two pieces into one once more.~
@2007 = ~Could it be you... my beloved, at last?~
@2008 = ~A quiet relief washes over you—the corrupted mythal’s grip does not reach this place.~
@2009 = ~(You feel the pull of the berry-shaped Ioun stone towards the tower. It may be a sign you are now able to enter its walls.)~
@2010 = ~(You do not have the berry-shaped Ioun stone. You can no longer enter the tower. Without the stone, the barrier is erected.)~
@2011 = ~A small jeweler’s anvil rests atop a larger one. Fragments of fine chains lie scattered nearby, as though many necklaces were once forged here. Strangely, the anvil radiates strong magic that seems untouched by the corrupted mythal.~
@2012 = ~None of the items in your inventory appear suitable for crafting a necklace upon this anvil.~
@2013 = ~Magic seems to function normally within this area.~
@2014 = ~This statue depicts an elven deity, but you find it difficult to recognize it.~
@2015 = ~This statue portrays Mythrien Sarath, a nearly forgotten god once revered for his guardianship over Mythals.~
@2016 = ~You recognize this statue as likely depicting Mythrien Sarath—a nearly forgotten elven god.~
@2017 = ~I AM THE POISON AND I SHALL DEVOUR YOU!~
@2018 = ~(You can hear some sound coming from the cauldron. It looks like with the death of the creature an antidote was created.)~
@2019 = ~Rose... it must be safe!~
@2020 = ~Take it to Mythrien! Place it under his feet and reach for his helping hand!~
@2021 = ~When you approach the ruins, you notice an ankheg that looked as if it was lured by the place, but when the creature notices you, it decides to attack.~  
@2022 = ~A statue of a young elven warrior-maiden, red roses blooming at her feet — the only plants untouched by the corrupted Mythal.~
@2023 = ~It seems you require something else to forge an amulet that shields you from the Mythal—apparently, an essence.~

@2024 = ~Blood... All I can see is blood!~
@2025 = ~Free me! Please!~
@2026 = ~(The yuan-ti is nowhere to be seen, but he couldn't have left Myth Unnohyr, he was too wounded for that.)~
@2027 = ~You're in Myth Unnohyr again. The path behind you is sealed by a wall of tangled growth. Your only escape lies ahead, through the heart of the shattered city.~
@2028 = ~Something unsettling stirs in the north. To reach it, you must pass through the sanctuary once claimed by the priest of Talona.~
@2029 = ~We should see our dryad-friend first. From what I understand, she has the sword.~
@2030 = ~We came for the Remembrance of the Myths, my friend. The High Priest knows about everything.~
@2031 = ~Yes. I know. And I was told to give you the sword. Even though I believe it should stay here. With me.~
@2032 = ~We do not have much choice.~
@2033 = ~There is always a choice.~
@2034 = ~Here. Take it. And I pray it won't become your doom. May Eldath watch over you.~
@2035 = ~Now I will send you to the hidden entrance of Myth Unnohyr, <CHARNAME>.~
@2036 = ~Farewell. May Eldath’s quiet breath shelter you.~
@2037 = ~Find our enemy, <CHARNAME>. Find the wyrd and use this sword against it. It should also break the barrier and let you leave that damned place.~
@2038 = ~We'll wait for your return.~
@2039 = ~If anyone is to win this battle, it's you.~
@2040 = ~The path behind you is sealed by a wall of tangled growth. Your only escape lies ahead, through the heart of the shattered city.~
@2041 = ~The entrance to this tower is shrouded in an unnatural mist. Without the proper means, you will not be able to enter.~

// ACPP 77 strings
@2042 = ~A proud elven warrior-maiden stands joyfully before her city.~
@2043 = ~She fights against numerous beasts.~
@2044 = ~The elven warrior-maiden appears to be stabilizing some magic.~
@2045 = ~An elven community mourns at a coffin.~

@2046 = ~You recognize Elv-Esster Aened, commander of the guard of Myth Unnohyr. She stands before the city – young, proud, and filled with hope.~
@2047 = ~She fights against numerous beasts – it seems the god Malar has a hand in this. Elv-Esster faces them alone – unyielding, without fear.~
@2048 = ~You realize she is trying to stabilize the failing mythal with her own essence – an act of sacrifice and magic.~
@2049 = ~The mourning elves in this image are not just witnesses to death, but to divine failure. Some lower their heads – others gaze accusingly at the sky.~

@2050 = ~An undead creature appears to be possessing an elf.~
@2051 = ~The elven warrior-maiden tries to drive back the undead.~
@2052 = ~The elven warrior-maiden seems to be torn apart by a blinding magical light.~

@2053 = ~Elv-Esster Aened's tomb~

@2054 = ~A ghostly entity cloaked in shadows appears to invade the mind of an elven defender – the Wyrd has come.~
@2055 = ~Elv-Esster Aened and her kin stand against the encroaching Wyrd, their spells lashing out in desperation.~
@2056 = ~A surge of wild magic erupts as the mythal shatters—Elv-Esster vanishes within the blinding light.~

// ACPP70 strings - the tree obstacle
@2060 = ~By the power of the wardstone, the throng of undead trees is banished.~
@2061 = ~You could try to move this mighty tree aside using an object, fire, or exceptionally great strength.~
@2062 = ~With sheer force, you actually manage to shift the tree aside.~
@2063 = ~You could try to move this mighty tree aside using an object, fire, or exceptionally great strength.~
@2064 = ~The tree collapses under the fire and dissolves.~
@2065 = ~The fire seems to slowly destroy the fallen tree.~
@2066 = ~The fire seems to have some effect on the fallen tree.~
@2067 = ~Now that the passage is clear, the wardstone crumbles to dust.~

@2068 = ~Temple of Mythrien~
@2069 = ~Mmm... oh-ho-ho! Hmmm. Such sweetness! Crunchy comb, golden nectar... *slurp* Ahhh, bliss indeed!~ [AC#PPHO0]
@2070 = ~Oh! By the Gentle Broodkeeper herself... I did not expect company while I indulged.~

// the two fairies
@2100 = ~If you must sparkle, do it over there!~
@2101 = ~But over there is boring!~
@2102 = ~Stop tugging my robe!~
@2103 = ~Fine, fine! We’ll tug your hair instead. Happy now?~
@2104 = ~Don’t trust fireflies. They’re just show-offs with no style.~
















